**Clinical Reasoning:**
Elevated serum bilirubin with low urine urobilinogen suggests impaired conjugated bilirubin excretion, pointing toward obstructive or hepatocellular damage affecting bile flow. While absent glucuronidation would raise unconjugated bilirubin, here the key finding—low urobilinogen—is consistent with reduced enterohepatic circulation due to obstruction downstream of the liver. Option D directly addresses defective hepatic bile excretion, aligning best with obstructive jaundice patterns seen in biliary outflow issues like choledocholithiasis or hilar stricture.

